This review is for the New Car Sales at Longo. Specifically calling out our sales guy Tony Hua and his Manager Casey Kabia. Typically if you were to say you got tag teamed by the dealer it would be a bad thing, but this is not the case for the dynamic duo of Tony Hua and his manager Casey Kabia. They really made the deal happen and they were going in with a difficult hand to begin with. I happen to be at Longo this past week getting one of my Toyotos serviced (which was also a pleasant experience this time as well) and decided to go check out the new Siennas. Our family is growing and we needed to find out more about the van. We did not expect to drive off with one. Tony was available and took me and my wife to the lot where all the Siennas were and let us take our time to get in every single one walked us calmly (never rushed) through all the diff models and when we couldnt decide on color he drove a few of them side by side so we could compare. That was amazing service. We told Tony that we have a lease ending for our Lexus and we wanted to run in one car for the the Sienna and we were a few months away from lease ending and didnt want to make two car payments. He said dont worry he promised the deal will happen and it did. After he negotiated with us and his manager he also talked with the leasing manager and worked with the managers of Lexus to make the transition smooth. We worked out all the details and setup an appointment to drop off the old and in with the new the next day. I brought in my Lexus the next day and he drove us back and forth between the Lexus and Toyota to handle the return of Lexus and paperwork for Toyota. Knowing it was taking a bit longer than expected he grabbed us some water. His constant follow up to ensure we were happy with our car was also a plus. Tony made sure our new Sienna was spotless and even helped us move all the junk we had from our old car into the new. Gave us some shopping bags to boot. I highly recommend Tony Hua. We have bought 3 cars in the past 4 years, 2 of them have been from Longo. This has by far been the best experience we have ever had in buying a new car in the last 10 years! When he promised the deal is going to happen it did. He said I wont be wasting your time if it wasnt going to happen. He promised and he delivered. We walked in with just wanting to find out more about the car and ended up buying it. He really made it really easy not to say no in a good way. Both my wife and I agree that we left with a smile on our faces, got a great deal and excellent hand holding service. We will be going to him from now on and I am recommending my family and friends to see him for sure. They deserve no less than a 5 star review!

Dr. Clarence Clottey has been my doctor as well as our family doctor for many years beginning from when he was resident in Ottawa. I have recommended many friends to him. Never have I seen a doctor so caring and dedicated. He takes time to thoroughly examine a case before prescribing some medication. Moreover the polite manner he receives his clients and his comforting words constitute part of the psychological healing process. Do you want holistic healing instead of the usual cosmetic healing from most doctors who begin to hurriedly prescribe before examination? If so, then go to Dr. Clarence Clottey and you will never be disappointed. I specially recommend him.

We were scheduled to induce labor at this hospital for the past month. We were given the time a week before hand, and when we showed up (10 minutes early) we were informed that our time was filled due to the hospital being full. I can understand that, but what is disappointing is the steps taken by the hospital afterwards. You would think they would say we are on standby for the next available room, but instead we were bumped 3 days later. This is unacceptable treatment in my opinion as the benefit of inducing is that you can have your family travel based on the circumstances. Now everyone will be here 3 days early, and IF we get in at the 3 day mark our family will have a day before they fly home. Thanks North Central Baptist!! You know how to make memories that are special for a family.

After my mom's GP did NOTHING to get to the bottom of my mom's problem (she had a staff infection in her right foot that would not clear up), our neighbor, formerly a KP dermatologist, Dr. John Shen, immediately wrote up a referral for my mom to see his "good friend", Dr. Daniel Miller (another FANTASTIC physician) who specializes in internal medicine. Dr. Miller in turn referred my mom right away to Dr. Canty (Dr. Shen suspected my mom's inability to get rid of the Staff infection stemmed from vascular problems). Well, Dr. Canty got to the bottom of the problem right away; he ran several tests and in no time diagnosed my mom's illness -- she had a VERY severe case of Peripheral Vascular Disease (if my memory serves me right, Dr. Canty said my mom had one of the worst cases he had ever seen). My mom had so little blood flow below the knee on her right leg, that the angiogram results didn't show any of the major blood vessels...just itty bitty "unnamed vessels&quo

I recently underwent surgery for breast reduction. Because I have Kaiser health insurance, I was worried that I would possibly just become a number and wind up less than pleased, they kept saying this surgery is not for aesthetic purposes and actually is a medical procedure. I have not had the bandages off yet, but if what I have experienced so far is an indication then I am overjoyed! Dr. Cissy was kind and informative as were her PAs , nurses, etc. She personally followed up and treated me like I was the only patient on her schedule. I'll see tomorrow how things look, and am sure to be pleased.

I am really disappointed that Kaiser does NOT have a birthing tub or any other options besides being stuck in a bed-in their birthing center. It is the furthest thing from nature to be stuck with monitors on you the entire time you are in labor, restricting movement and making labor very slow. There are showers, but no tubs. My wife wanted our children to be there to see their sister be born and they also did not want that either, which was upsetting to us as well. It just felt very sterile and not very family oriented at all. My wife loves her doctors and our pediatrician, but we were really disappointed in this aspect of Kaiser.

Upon reading the other statements about this professional, I have to agree. She would rather see you sacrificed than do her job. The experience I had was that she returns calls at her leisure. I decided to pick another person. I actually know someone who had a better experience with her husband who is in same practice. I believe if you decide Galindo & Assoc. proceed with much caution. Also, I read Elizabeth post. I'm not sure who you have for attorney, but want you to know it is not constitutional for a civil court to order any citizen to go to a private party and pay money for services. Why would we put decisions in hands of party we don't choose? There is no statute or law that supports the ability to order persons to leave the court of law and pay an outside party to make decision. And, shouldn't we be asking what are Galindo's qualifications to be "appointed" by a court. There is no process for this "appointment". There is mediation department and that is free. Not sure what is your situation, but recommend if you have to go to Galindo, don't sign any authorization with her to release your information, this may hopeful prevent her from doing something to harm your case. She should only communicate with court through testimony. She is not able to talk to anyone about your information without release. When I read on here about her actions with other, I think I could help someone avoid pitfalls. I think sometime we react without thinking when court tells you to do something, this is civil law, not criminal. Court can't order these things.

I am very pleased so far with my results. I am only 4 weeks post op from a BA and u/l ab and flank lipo. I had very little pain and a speedy recovery. Easy recovery = less trauma = less pain. I would recommend Dr. Freedland to friends and family. I would like to mention that the Lakes Surgical facility where my surgery was performed was FANTASTIC. They (the nurses) were all so nice and made me feel so comfortable and calm. They also had great things to say about Dr. Freedland. He may not have a lot of time to spend with you, or have a super sweet/nice/overly caring bedside manner...but if you want a skilled PS, who will give you great results then he is the one to choose.

Dr. Jabara seemed like a compassionate physician at first. However, after just one visit in-person, it became obvious that he was primarily interested in achieving his own goals rather than ours. We recognize that every medical case is unique and challenging in its own way; but we are firm believers that the patient should have some input into his/her own medical care. Dr. Jabara was the first reproductive specialist that we saw and he immediately decided that IVF was the only way that he would be willing to help us. He flat out refused to order very low-risk, minimally-invasive procedures that could aid our ability to conceive naturally and would not entertain IVF-alternatives that we wanted to consider. It is important for those struggling with infertility to recognize that Reproductive-Endocrinology-Infertility (REI) specialists are often graded/rated based on their success in attaining pregnancy on the first attempt. Additionally, IVF is a very lucrative business for REI specialists. While IVF may be the most time-efficient way for some to achieve pregnancy, many people do not have the $20K to cover its cost and others may have reservations about embarking on an IVF journey from an ethical perspective. In our case, we simply preferred to try more natural options and advance to IVF, only if necessary. Conflicting views and ulterior motives, on his part, resulted in Dr. Jabara requesting that we seek care from another specialist. This was incredibly hurtful on top of the pain that infertility, alone, brings. Dr. Jabara and his staff are disorganized, chronically late and do not take care to keep patient information confidential. Based on other online reviews, if you're already certain that IVF is the path you'd like to take, he may, in fact, be a reasonable option for you. However, if you are new to infertility or would like to discuss a variety of methods of attaining a viable pregnancy with a compassionate physician who will listen to your concerns, we recommend that you go elsewhere (i.e. to another location - not even to this office at 4900 Sunset Blvd). If you do decide to see Dr. Jabara or one of the team members at Kaiser Sunset, we suggest that you make sure you have all of your research and documentation (every lab test for both partners, every ultrasound result, every historical piece of information and all of your goals/ideals) physically with you each and every time you go to your appointments, especially prior to procedures. If they take your paperwork to scan it into the system, be sure to get it back and bring it to all future appointments. (This is somewhat less of a concern if you and your spouse have obtained all healthcare within the Southern California Kaiser system). Each time you or your spouse get labs done, request that the doctor review each lab with you and confirm that all required tests have been satisfactorily completed. Finally, dont expect this team to provide you with a great deal of support when it comes to conceiving, especially if you would like to consider any option that differs from their recommended treatment plan. In summation, our experience with Dr. Jabara and the REI team at Kaiser Sunset was abysmal (If we could give ZERO stars, we would). If this is your only option for infertility care, we have listed some ways that may help you get the most out of your experience. We write this review in hopes of preventing others from having the same sort of experience we did. Signed, Future Great Parents

While IVF may be the most time-efficient way for some to achieve pregnancy, many people do not have the $20K to cover its cost and others may have reservations about embarking on an IVF journey from an ethical perspective. In our case, we simply preferred to try more natural options and advance to IVF, only if necessary. Conflicting views and ulterior motives, on his part, resulted in Dr. Jabara requesting that we seek care from another specialist. This was incredibly hurtful on top of the pain that infertility, alone, brings. Dr. Jabara and his staff are disorganized, chronically late and do not take care to keep patient information confidential. Based on other online reviews, if you're already certain that IVF is the path you'd like to take, he may, in fact, be a reasonable option for you. However, if you are new to infertility or would like to discuss a variety of methods of attaining a viable pregnancy with a compassionate physician who will listen to your concerns, we recommend that you go elsewhere (i.e. to another location - not even to this office at 4900 Sunset Blvd). If you do decide to see Dr. Jabara or one of the team members at Kaiser Sunset, we suggest that you make sure you have all of your research and documentation (every lab test for both partners, every ultrasound result, every historical piece of information and all of your goals/ideals) physically with you each and every time you go to your appointments, especially prior to procedures. If they take your paperwork to scan it into the system, be sure to get it back and bring it to all future appointments. (This is somewhat less of a concern if you and your spouse have obtained all healthcare within the Southern California Kaiser system). Each time you or your spouse get labs done, request that the doctor review each lab with you and confirm that all required tests have been satisfactorily completed. Finally, dont expect this team to provide you with a great deal of support when it comes to conceiving, especially if you would like to consider any option that differs from their recommended treatment plan. In summation, our experience with Dr. Jabara and the REI team at Kaiser Sunset was abysmal (If we could give ZERO stars, we would). If this is your only option for infertility care, we have listed some ways that may help you get the most out of your experience. We write this review in hopes of preventing others from having the same sort of experience we did. Signed, Future Great Parents

My wife had to go to er due to extreme stomach pain. The er staff diagnosed her with diverticulitis and had her admitted and put on antibiotics. We found the hospitalist very difficult to communicate with. The long and short of it is: my wife was discharged on th e7th day there and within a week was in St. Josephs hospital where she was diagnosed with stage 4 colon cancer. She passed away from the cancer 90 days after the diagnosis. How can a person go to an er (west valley) and be diagnosed with diverticulitis and not the cancer? The locals in the west valley have nicknamed the place death valley hospital.

The flu shot clinic is extremely efficient. They are open 9-5 m-Sat and I got to their parking lot at 4:54 and was racing around worried I wouldn't make it in time and when I found the clinic (right in the middle of the whole building next to the vision center) I asked the lady if they were closed and she was like oh no honey, don't worry you have plenty of time (it was 459pm by then) and even though we both knew I BARELY made it in time, she made me feel welcome and much better just for saying I had plenty of time! I appreciate that so much because I'm used to most places closing five minutes before they close and rolling their eyes and sighing at me when it's that close to closing time! So I had to praise this lady for being so nice to me and not making me feel uncomfortable and unwanted like other places always do! There was no line (perhaps partly because they were almost closed) but they were super fast, and there were five nurses still available at closing time. All of the staff were smiling and making me feel welcome. I appreciate this kind of service because it's so rare now a days! So thank you Kaiser flu clinic staff =))

Dr. Shayya did not seem willing to discuss side effects of the medications she was trying to prescribe and indeed did not even want to have a discussion about which medication should be presribed. She used medical terms that would not be easily understood by those without medical degrees. When ordering blood work, she did not clarify what it meant to have "fasting" labs done, and appeared annoyed when the patient requested further information. She quickly brushed off symptoms the patient was trying to discuss with her, as she felt they were unrelated to the condition being diagnosed and therefore unimportant. "Bedside Manner" is apparently something this physician sees as irrelevant in being a competent doctor.

Worst doctor experience ever! First, I had to wait almost 2 hours past scheduled appointment time just to be called from the waiting room. I had severe pain, he ran a bunch of tests, he didn't explain what he was doing or what the results were, he's had no follow up. I'm out hundreds of dollars & still don't know what's wrong or worse what I even paid for. Don't waste your time & money!

Katina understood exactly where we the parents were coming from when we met her with our 9 yr old son and his aggression and anger problems. We were at our wits end and finally decided to pursue his symptoms medically. We didn't want to change his personality, when he was having a good day he lit up the room, very enthusiastic and inquisitive. We didn't want that to change. My son liked her the very minute he met her and that is very important. She explained the procedures to both of us and the medication to both of us, making sure my son understood just as much as me. She talked to him and when he was distracted by the toys in her office, she talked to me but was very patient and persistent with my son. He understood the ground rules for her office visits, like talking to her and than he could play while she talked with me. She didn't dismiss our concerns about a narcotic and made us very aware of other options and all options and ultimately our decision was THE decision. We will miss her now that we no longer are with Kaiser.

She is a great & dependable obgyn. I was in my 2nd trimester when I started seeing her. At first, the staff seems distant however after sometime you got to know them, they were actually really nice and helpful. The office is a decent size and very cozy but sometimes can be overcrowded when Dr. Lawton was away for delivery and the patients were piling. Sometimes I feel rushed however if you could sit down and open your notes (I always jot down in a notebook my list of questions), she would always answer all of it. She also respect my wishes regarding episiotomy and pain management. One thing that I learn after delivering my first child experience is to always trust your gut and ask questions (every bit of it). I had a hunch that my baby is big however I never really pressed the issue with her thinking that I was overboard about it. In the end, I had a succesful c-section operation with her. Overall, I would recommend her to all my friends and will see her for the next pregnancy.

I had the pleasure of being under the care of Doctor Riopelle from 2006 - 2012 (My company dropped Kaiser). He was recently voted as a "Top Doc" by 5280 magazine. The rest of the world is finally seeing what I've know all along, he is without question a "Top Doc". I met Dr. Riopelle under some less than desirable circumstances. I was 44 years old with symptoms of a biliary duct blockage, similar to a gallstone. unfortunately it didn't turn out to be a gallstone but was a cholangiocarcinoma (Bile duct cancer). My symptoms were not normal for a bile duct cancer patient, making it difficult to diagnose. One of the most impressive things to me about Dr Riopelle is his dedication to finding what the issue is and working to an accurate diagnosis/treatment. There is no doubt in my mind I'm alive because of Dr. Riopelle and his ability to diagnose my issue very early. When we talked about my issues early on, he didn't talk about statistics, reoccurance, remission, he talked about full resection and cure. it's been over 7 years since my diagnosis, I've cancer free since the day of my surgery, check out the 5 year survival rates for bile duct cancer, you want Dr. Riopelle on your team. I'm living proof that choosing the right Doctor can be a life or death decision. Easy choice...Dr Riopelle.

I have been his patient for 35 years I think of him so highly that I left the Medicare HMO when he stopped accepting HMO payments. He does not accept Medicare or other Insurance payments but will file for you. I don't mind the long wait in his office because when he sees me he spends 20 to 30 minutes or as long as it takes for me to be satisfied that all my questions have been answered. Unlike other doctors he does not rush out to see the next patient and gives the feeling that he is totally committed to you for the duration. His diagnoses is excellent and I have met strangers who claim that they would not be alive if it wasn't for his quick diagnosis. His rapport with specialists is excellent and when he sends me to one I am assured that he chooses them based on his assessment of how good they are. I would recommend him to any body looking for a competent internist - just remember to take a good book to read while in the waiting room !!!

I recently went to see Dr. Hiles at the new Kaiser facility and my experience was fantastic! My previous doctor retired and I needed a new doctor as soon as possible. Dr. Hiles and her staff made the transition really smooth for me. I read some of the other comments and people need to understand that doctors don't have any control over other departments. Especially in the case of referrals. Kaiser also restricts the type of pain meds that can be prescribed by doctors that accept Kaiser. I'm on meds and understand that I can't walk into ANY doctors office with a self diagnosis and demand a particular drug. I'm not a doctor and would never think that I was qualified to tell a doctor what his or her job was. As far as meds for depression, Kaiser limits what can be prescribed by their doctors. It is up to a psychiatrist to properly diagnose and prescribe the right meds. Add to that the many months of adjustments it takes to really get the doses dialed in. I really liked my first appointment and will continue seeing Dr. Hiles.

I'm on meds and understand that I can't walk into ANY doctors office with a self diagnosis and demand a particular drug. I'm not a doctor and would never think that I was qualified to tell a doctor what his or her job was. As far as meds for depression, Kaiser limits what can be prescribed by their doctors. It is up to a psychiatrist to properly diagnose and prescribe the right meds. Add to that the many months of adjustments it takes to really get the doses dialed in. I really liked my first appointment and will continue seeing Dr. Hiles.

I found Dr Ellis 10 years ago, and she has been the most wonderful internist I have ever had.. She knows me and my body. I was hospitalized this past summer for bacterial meningitis, and Dr Ellis spoke with all my doctors, texted me what was going on, because i was out of it, and it was beyond my realm of understanding. Dr Ellis spends time with me in her office, gives accurate diagnosis, has saved me with the follow-up visits, because I have a long recovery. I recommend Dr Ellis to anyone, you will be very very satisfied with your care.

Although I know this sounds harsh, Dr. Fee is essentially participating in insurance fraud and she is a woefully negligent physician. If there were a zero stars option, I would be clicking on that one. I could go on and on about the fact that she was my doctor for over one year while I had a female issue I needed to get checked out, and yet of all my visits, I only saw her in person one time, for 5 minutes, to tell me essentially nothing. I waited one hour in the waiting room and half an hour in the examination room just to see her for 5 minutes. It was clear she had never even read my file until that very minute. After this 5 minute visit, Dr. Fee (without my knowledge or consent) sent a prescription for a random estrogen cream to my Express Scripts pharmacy and ordered three auto refills. WE NEVER EVEN DISCUSSED the prescription and I certainly DON'T NEED IT. I am already taking an estrogen pill and I certainly would never need an estrogen topical cream!  I was charged one hundred dollars multiple times for this cream-- I called her office and had to go back and forth with the manager and practically threatened them with legal action over the course of three weeks until I reached Dr. Fee. Her response was that doctors and patients talk about a lot of things in their visits and I must have forgotten. She is the one seeing dozens of patients a day and yet I'm the one who forgot about an estrogen cream I supposedly need in the rare 5 minute meeting I had with her? She then said that she orders the cream for a lot of her patients on a trial basis and that it wasn't her fault that my pharmacy filled the prescription (she knows that Express Scripts works on a mail-order, auto-charge basis so this not any sort of justification for her actions).  She is rude, irresponsible, and in my opinion most likely fraudulent in her activities with whatever pharmaceutical company is working with her to order estrace cream for any patient that walks in her door and may be a candidate for this random cream that your insurance pays $280 dollars per unit for.  $280 dollars. One tube of cream. Every month. If hundreds of patients are having the same experience...you can do the math and figure out why any doctor would be doing this this and save yourself from what I went through. My pharmacy, my insurance--Anthem Blue Cross, and my credit card company are currently investigating her actions. Please don't waste your time and money with this horrible, horrible doctor. A doctor's visit for a female issue should be one of calm and reassurance, not long waits, stress, pressure, and then thievery. This is one of the most ridiculous events I have ever gone through in my life and I highly suggest that prospective patients look elsewhere for a positive experience with their doctor.

Dr. Mehta took no time to 'warm up' to my 2 year old son. Consequently, when he came at my child with an instrument, my child started to cry. He's TWO. Dr Mehta asked if 'he was always like this?" which I thought was really rude. Again, he's TWO.Then when my child resisted having his eye pried open he said, "We can do this the easy way or the hard way." Who talks like that to a 2 year old??Later, my child was then munching on cheerios while waiting for him to come back and he snapped "No more cheerios! No more cheerios!" I SAID NO MORE CHEERIOS!" at my hearing impaired 79 year old father that was giving my son a snack after waiting so long. I just don't understand why he works with children since they seem to irritate him so much. It's baffling.

My husband has been seeing Dr. Miao since l987 for bleeding ulcerative colitis which was very severe. Dr. Miao treated him until it went into remission. He has annual colonoscopies and has NEVER had any pain or discomfort in the slightest from those procedures. In fact my husband also raves about how gentle he is. And both my husband and Dr. Miao have had bypass surgery within one year of each other and Dr. Miao has done a LOT of research on heart related issues and is extremely well informed. He always shows concern not just for Gary's intestinal health but also for his heart health as well. I started going to Dr. Miao about 10 years ago for acid reflux and a colonoscopy because of my age. I couldn't agree with my husband more. He has performed both the colonoscopy on me as well as the endoscopy and he's always been gentle and I have not experienced any discomfort. I would highly recommend him.

I just had half of my thyroid removed with Dr. Hoff and he was wonderful. He just happened to find a nodule on my thyroid during a consultation for a possible tonsillectomy. He was very helpful and knowledgeable and always made me feel very comfortable. I had to get two needle aspirations before he decided that the actual surgery would be necessary to rule out thyroid cancer, and he was able to fit me in for both in the same week. If you are going in for thyroid surgery, I would look no further. I also plan on going back to him in about a year for my tonsils. Great doctor! He is not arrogant like the way many surgeons can seem, he is very kind and obviously extremely intelligent.

I have been fighting mental illness for over 10 years and seen COUNTLESS doctors. I can't even remember how many psychiatrists, primary care docs, endocro. docs, therapists, researchers, etc. etc. I was even treated at a "premier" psychiatric hospital and did not have as good a doctor! In all those years, Dr. Siddiqi is THE 1st DOCTOR who has truly listened, diagnosed and treated me accurately! She did not simply "push meds" on me, but rather took into account my entire medical history and condition. I can honestly say I am not sure if I would still "be here" if it weren't for Dr. Siddiqi. She is WONDERFUL! She is very busy simply due to the number of patients who need help in the field of Mental Health. But, she always takes the time to truly allow you to speak your mind, she asks pertinent questions, wants to understand your overall quality-of-life and makes you feel as though she truly cares. She emails within the Kaiser system as quickly as she can -- and thoroughly answers your questions and concerns. I think, especially in the field of Mental Health, she is AMAZING!

After receiving a papillary thyroid cancer diagnosis, the radiologist who performed my biopsy recommended Dr. Purkert for the surgery. After reading the reviews for Dr. Purkert on Healthgrades.com , vitals.com , and in various discussion boards related to thyroid cancer, I decided to move forward with him.  My wife and I were highly anxious about this situation, but Dr. Purkert's calm and patient demeanor went a long way towards setting us at ease. He rationally and unhurriedly explained everything about the surgery, the disease itself, and went over all questions we had. It's hard to say anything is "great" related to cancer, but really the experience is best described as such. He took all the time we needed, and we never felt rushed. Plus, he has a very calm way about him that was reassuring.  As for the surgery, he performed it remarkably at Inova Fairfax Hospital. The man has skill, for sure. He removed the entire thyroid, but was able to save all four parathyroids. In fact, he even removed one parathyroid, checked it for cancer, and re-implanted it successfully. No nerve damage/vocal changes. I am only six months out, and already the scar is shockingly small.  I feel it was a wise decision to go with Dr. Purkert. His positive reputation in thyroid surgeries is well-deserved.

Very, very capable doctor and staff at this location. They specialize in high risk pregnancies. Dr. Mason is also a trained surgeon so he has experience with emergencies. The staff is accomodating and very nice. The doctors listen to women, acknowledging their concerns and fears, as well as helping through them with offering up helpful advice. There is no condescending tone here, nor is there any rush to get a patient out of the office so they can move on to the next patient. They take their time and welcome any questions you may have. This practice is located at St. John Hospital so there is plenty of parking; however, you need to pay for it. It is $2 to park in the back of the hospital or $4 to use the Valet. Usually, they give a parking voucher to cover the cost but not sure if they still do this.

i recently moved back to the area after 3 years away and wanted to find a new ob.gyn as I was not impressed with the one I had previously. i don't need my doctor to be mushy but i do need someone who will talk straight and give me the facts, without being too brutal. Dr Hamilton was very pleasant and attentive. He did not dismiss my concerns or make light of any of my past ( complicated ) history. He gave me his opinion, and his thoughts on potential treatment but didn't give me the hard sell. He sent me away with literature to think about it. His staff are all very nice too, I did not have to wait too long for my appointment ( its obviously a busy practice) my first visit I waited 15 mins, my 2nd visit only about 4 mins.There is on site parking which is helpful and I was able to get an early morning appointment on both occasions. I certainly would recommend him, and i read all his Yelp reviews before making an appointment.Be warned his waiting area is very small ( about 5 chairs) and full of kids toys, so watch out not to step on toddlers or Fisher Price talking phones.

So until last week I didn't even know Doc's had yelp reviews. Found Dr. Blank after a desperate search to find a new Doc after a bad experience with another one. This after my beloved Gyn-Onc of many years left the area and left The Wicked Witch of the West in her place. But, I digress.... So I've had one appointment with Dr. Blank (stay tuned for updates) and YES YES YES. He was so friendly and patient. Sat and listed to my concerns, went to help another patient and then brought me to his office so that he could talk next steps and make sure I understood what was happening going forward. I have to say its sometimes too much of a rarity to find a Doc who takes the time to listen to patients. I get it, its a tough field and generally far too many patients to see in one day. Well, somehow Dr. Blank makes it work and I am forever grateful. I have to say I shed a tear or two when I left the office. Been struggling with some pretty serious side effects from my medical illnesses and its been a long hard road getting someone to understand that I'm still too young to feel this way. He listened and immediately provided options. Gave me my prescription, my referral and even recommended a Doctor I can see for another issue I'm having. He even made a copy of my medical records himself! In any case, I'm sticking with this one. Its not easy to have to re-explain a complicated medical history every time you walk into an office. Sometimes I get so overwhelmed that I leave wondering if the Doctor really understands what I am going thru. Didn't feel that way this time, left feeling like I've got a Doctor in my corner who's going to make sure I have the best quality of life regardless of what my medical records say. What a gem!

She was not willing to hear any suggestions regarding my condition that were not lockstep with the American Medical Association's handbook. If you are diagnosed with a neurological disorder, she is a great place to start as she will do a good job at describing the condition that you are suffering from, but will not work with you at all to treat it. Her response is take some meds, if that doesn't work, increase your meds, if that doesn't work, up the dosage a little more.

Dr. Buchanan cares about her patients, and takes the time to listen to concerns and, address all medical issues. Dr. Buchanan is a brilliant and exceptional doctor that has gone beyond her call of duty to help me. She instantly put a medical plan in order to prevent further injury to my brain by providing thorough medical examinations, prescribing the appropriate medications for my illness, assembling a team of specialist to find any causes or diseases that may be afflicting my health, ordering extensive laboratory testing, and using her wealth of medical knowledge to ensure that my care is above standard.Dr. Buchanan takes the time to read all results from each process and procedure, as well as monitoring my health closely. I have never encountered a doctor of her caliber in my lifetime; she is truly an advocate for her patients. Through her professionalism, care, and concern, she has given me hope that I will continue lifes journey. I will forever be eternally grateful for all that she has done for me as a doctor and as a compassionate human being.

I was a first time Patient trying to get established and so to make it easy on the Dr. and his office I brought with me some old lab records, I was needing a refill on some medication and I though this would help in expediting getting the refills. Well after waiting for over 1 hr in the office and not being kept in the loop at to what was taking so long or that he was running behind he finally walks in and sees me. He asks all the normal questions and does a brief exam and get a history medical background and I show him the labs, then I get the refill. Well then I get a bill for a large amount when he billed my insurance stating that He Diagnosed me with the problems I told him I already had and was needing the medication for and will not change the billing so that the insurance will pay for it. I will no ever go back to him again and I was going to have my family go to him but not now. He is just in it for the money ;

Dr. Stokes was very rude from the very beginning. She was never polite in any kind of way and she didn't seem to care at all on the rude tone on her voice she carrier. Her bedside manners are very very bad. We've been with other pediatricians in the past and comparing it she doesn't have the caring manner a normal pediatrician has for children and/or the patient's family. The look in her face always seemed like she was in a bad mood and only wanted to get in and get out, and just get over the visit. I am sorry, but if you are to say a professional Dr. who owns a practice, you don't carry an awful character towards your patients. She doesn't have the caring feelings any other Doctor should have. Every time we said something she would answer with a "what" with an attitude. It's called be polite and say "excuse me?" Or "I beg your pardon?" Or "I am sorry can you repeat that again." Little to say I over heard her say bad words before speaking of whatever with her coworkers. By the way this is a PEDIATRICS place where there are CHILDREN around all the time. She will be very upfront and not give a care in the world of how her words come out. To all the Doctors out there I'm sorry for someone like Dr. Stokes who give a bad name to the subject Dr. I've been around so many and me knowing one in my family this is not what a Doctor should EVER be. She will also find the smallest excuse to bring a patient in only to send them to a different place for them to get checked. I wouldn't be surprise she does it for the money. Prescribes antibiotics for EVERYTHING and anything. Also booking early appointments with her is a huge NO, NO! Apparently she had other children to see at hospitals before her out practice, yet she still says is available to see patients early in the mornings. Long waits, waiting to happen. I'm surprise she still has patients to see nowadays.

I'm not sure where to start, as I do not wish to disclose too many details of my case, in fear of litigation.But I would never recommend this doctor to anyone.Expect to wait 3 hours, minimum, for your visit, especially if you go in the summer. On Mondays, during clinic, the reception looks like a third world hospital, with patients being seen as late as 9 pm. All of us knew to pack lots of food and all of our prescriptions - this was tough to learn the first time around. Not at all comfortable if you're in a cast, in a wheelchair, etc.There are two PAs here, and one has an atrocious bedside manner. He has made horrible comments to me and most of the patients I knew felt similarly. One of the ortho techs made several inappropriate comments to me. The front receptionist is a barracuda - very rude. Emailing any of the staff for insurance questions, general questions, whatever - it's like emailing a black hole. Not very responsive.Again, I can't go into details, but what I witnessed while undergoing treatment...it was by far the worst time of my life. My trust in the doctor was severely violated. I saw serious violations of ethics. I saw gross ineptitude. Was it all worth it? I don't know. I still have severe pain and severe problems, and the original problem I sought help for wasn't alleviated. I will be searching out doctors elsewhere.

It has been a long time since I have visited a doctor who actually called you immediately after tests results come back, even at night after office hours, and explained everything thoroughly--instead of requiring you to track down the results or leaving an unhelpful message on your voice mail. And every time I have needed an emergency appointment, he was very helpful. Plus, all of the specialists he has referred me to have been excellent.

As a young child, I received 3rd degree burns over most of my body. My prognosis for survival was "if God see fit for her to live, then she will". The doctors asked my parents to sign me over to the hospital for care, because some of the procedures performed were experimental and may need to be done at any time and trying to locate and obtain consent from my parents would be too time consuming and may risk my life. If I survived then they have to be prepared for the possibility that I may not be able to walk or use my arms again and my mental state was a factor; I may become depressed, withdrawn and suicidal. After many surgeries, blood transfusions, a coma, and respiratory therapy, I survived the burns; then came the physical therapy, to regain the use of my hands, arms and legs. Physical Therapy began in the hospital and then on outpatient bases three days a week for months and finally once a week for another year. I estimate it took close to two years for me to regain full use of my arms and legs, with some weakness in both, I was able to walk again, comb my hair and put on my own clothes.The hardest thing for me during this ordeal was the loneliness and isolation in my hospital room; many children came, went and some even died and at times my only constant friends were the people in the clouds. My bed was placed next to the window, where I laid flat on my back for many weeks, looking up and out of the window at the clouds. After awhile the clouds would take on forms of people and animals, and I could visualize many events happening in those clouds. Thus the loving, devotion and kindness of the nurses, doctors, staff, and my parents were sometimes my only contact with the outside world. My hospital room did not have a working television set. Well as all of you see I survived my ordeal, grew up and had a regular life, just like every other normal person; I became a working productive tax paying citizen, dated, got married and divorced and had a child. And I have never forgotten my experiences in the Burn Unit of Receiving Hospital and one person who really stood out from the others, encouraged me to try and walk use my hands and to not let my physical appearance discourage me from being with other people, his name was Dr. Shelton. Even though it has been years since my life and death experience with Receiving Hospital, I am glad to see that the hospital is still providing care. Recently I had to go to Receiving Hospital to take some tests and I received excellent service from the staff and it felt almost like coming home. I realize my sentiments of gratitude maybe late; however better late than never, Thank You Receiving Hospital for Saving my Life!!

If I survived then they have to be prepared for the possibility that I may not be able to walk or use my arms again and my mental state was a factor; I may become depressed, withdrawn and suicidal. After many surgeries, blood transfusions, a coma, and respiratory therapy, I survived the burns; then came the physical therapy, to regain the use of my hands, arms and legs. Physical Therapy began in the hospital and then on outpatient bases three days a week for months and finally once a week for another year. I estimate it took close to two years for me to regain full use of my arms and legs, with some weakness in both, I was able to walk again, comb my hair and put on my own clothes.The hardest thing for me during this ordeal was the loneliness and isolation in my hospital room; many children came, went and some even died and at times my only constant friends were the people in the clouds. My bed was placed next to the window, where I laid flat on my back for many weeks, looking up and out of the window at the clouds. After awhile the clouds would take on forms of people and animals, and I could visualize many events happening in those clouds. Thus the loving, devotion and kindness of the nurses, doctors, staff, and my parents were sometimes my only contact with the outside world. My hospital room did not have a working television set. Well as all of you see I survived my ordeal, grew up and had a regular life, just like every other normal person; I became a working productive tax paying citizen, dated, got married and divorced and had a child. And I have never forgotten my experiences in the Burn Unit of Receiving Hospital and one person who really stood out from the others, encouraged me to try and walk use my hands and to not let my physical appearance discourage me from being with other people, his name was Dr. Shelton. Even though it has been years since my life and death experience with Receiving Hospital, I am glad to see that the hospital is still providing care. Recently I had to go to Receiving Hospital to take some tests and I received excellent service from the staff and it felt almost like coming home. I realize my sentiments of gratitude maybe late; however better late than never, Thank You Receiving Hospital for Saving my Life!!

I don't normally rate anything other than food establishments, but this Kaiser location merits a quick review due to my experience there a couple of hours ago. This morning, I ate it on my bicycle shooting underneath the 5 into Little Italy. I tried to make a quick left onto the first one way there (the one right before India) and I clipped some concrete. Basically yard-saled all my shit. Anyways, among the multitude of scrapes, bruises, and cuts, I had a huge laceration on my left elbow that bled like a mutha. Being paranoid about infection, I called up Kaiser wondering if I should go see my doc and they asked a bunch of questions including when I'd last had a tetanus shot. Shit, tetanus? Really? I hadn't even though of that. Next thing I knew (after being told I probably didn't need to see a physician), I went into the nurses' clinic at Kaiser to get my gash treated and I needed a tetanus shot.  Yes, parking was easy and the waiting room had decent material including Bon Appetit, Newsweek, and People. But this place stands out because of two people I encountered at Kaiser today. Unfortunately, I never got their names. However, the first woman worked at the front desk around 1:45 pm; she was super cordial, quick, and efficient. Yet what most stood out was when she asked about the tattoo I had on my left forearm, which is part of a poem I wrote for my father when he passed. I'm always more than happy to read/explain the poem since my dad was awesome, so I loved that she took an interest and opened up to me about her father having recently passed. Whatever your name is, you were awesome to talk with today. A real service professional! The second woman, the nurse, was super friendly as well. Answered all of my questions, alleviated a lot of my fears, gave me the shot nice and quick and painless. She redressed the wound, bandaged it, and, to top it off, gave me a weeks worth of medical supplies that are WAY better than the bandages I was using. I mean, she wrapped up this wound so good, give me a cotton elbow sleeve and everything. I left feeling like an injured, professional athlete. All in all, a great experience. And I paid nothing! The cherry on top of my (bloody) sundae! Final note: Thank God I wore my helmet! Seriously, people who ride their bikes without a helmet in a fast paced environment will need more than a tetanus shot, bandages, and Neosporin. They'll need like, say, I don't know, full-scale hospice. Do yourself a favor, get over not looking cool, and wear a helmet. That's my diatribe for the day.

I really love Dr. Restivo. She is an extremely intelligent and sincere doctor. The weight loss program she created is amazing; everyone in the office gets healthier. I met the patient  with pancreatic cancer that she helped. After Dr. Restivo worked with this pancreatic cancer patient for 5months she had another PET scan. Based on the results of all her tests, her oncologist told her she did not need to see him for 6 months. She cried she was so elated with the news. She is truly grateful to Dr. Restivo and I am truly grateful for all she has done for me. I have an opportunity to talk with many of the patients and they all lose many pounds in inches quickly, and they feel great while they are losing the weight and after. We all love the cold laser treatments because they feel so good and we notice that we feel happier after the treatments. I read in a New Laser Therapy technology book that it can increase serotonin, maybe that is why we feel happier. I also read that it can increase melatonin which helps people have a more restful nights sleep. Many of the patients said they had sleep problems when they first came to see Dr. Restivo and now they sleep wonderfully and have great energy during the day.

I go here for my girly appointments. I appreciate having the option to see a nurse practitioner instead of a doctor. I love being able to make appointments online and that you can also place prescription refill orders online and your meds are mailed directly to you. (Great way to avoid pharmacy lines.) My Women's Health NP, Harriet Feltman, always takes time to check in with me about general health issues. During my last appointment we somehow discovered that we both have musical backgrounds. After my appointment, she took the time to print out information about a local music group that she performs with and provided her personal e-mail in case I had questions about visiting a rehearsal. On my way to an appointment I got a flat tire and ended up late. I worried that they would turn me away and make me come back anther day, but they completely understood and went out of their way to make sure I didn't have to reschedule. The doctor even called me after my appointment to fill me in on test results and such. Although this hospital no longer has an ER, it fills all my non-emergency needs just fine.

They always make an extra effort to be polite and courteous.

I chose Dr. Morales when I was at Beaver Medical Group because he did his Residency at USC School of Medicine and I worked at USC University Hospital and was on disability at the time he was doing his Residency. I chose the right doctor out of five I had tried. He is excellent, gets Referrals I request or any other physician requests. The first time I saw him, he told me if I had any problems to give him a call, and as I walked out of his office he gave me a big smile and a thumbs up. Can't ask for anything more. I sometimes have problems with one of his staff members, but overall, their care is very good. This is one of the top rated Medical Groups in Riverside and San Bernardino County, CA. He has to be my pain physician when I have a flare up and does his best to keep it controlled when I am hospitalized, although a pain management team would of course be better, but I wouldn't leave him unless I moved.

Insider's secret. Dr. Anne White is well-known as the go to expert in Cosmetic Surgery in the Winston-Salem, Greensboro, High Point area. While the office itself is unpretentious (it is not a large space), it is tastefully decorated, comfortable and attractive. The office staff if friendly. welcoming and knowledgable Dr. White is kind, sincere, knowledgable, ethical and talented. I feel comfortable with Dr. Anne White and trust her. I have now for 15 years. I recommend her without hesitation.

She explained everything she needed to do before the surgery and what she would do during it and what I could expect the process of healing to be like. She allowed me to choose the type of anesthetic I would have, epidural, which was very important to me. Although the nurses at SNHMC did not know how to use the machines I was hooked up to properly Karen remedied the mistake quickly after my surgery. She continues to be supportive of my overall health issues (I have Hep. C) although I don't need to see her very often any more.

I went to Piedmont OBGYN for over 20 yrs. I switched to Dr. Richardson about 10 yrs. ago. I was diagnosed with breast cancer after it was missed for at least 3 yrs. I did research on my file. My report came back probably not cancer & no other test were performed until the next yr. Dr. Richardson stated "about 80 % come back that way & I don't order another test. I don't feel 1 bit responsible for this." If the test are only 20% right, then something needs to change. This is NOT acceptable. I went to CTCA in Chicago for treatment. Frye Care & Piedmont OBGYN missed this for over 3 yrs. 3 spots on 1 breast & small spots on other that POBGYN & Frye Care never saw. Stage 3, when it could have been easily removed earlier. I have never went back & I feel sorry for the women that do.

So like most of you I've been going to the doctor for check ups and regularly scheduled visits my whole life. I have had my share of good visits and not so good visits and as an athlete and top tier Personal Trainer it's important that I stay healthy and be in the best possible shape I can which means if I get sick or injured, seeing a good doctor is VITAL to recovery so I can get back out there and do what I love , Train! I wasn't quite sure of kaiser permanente as I've heard pro's and cons about the system and have had military insurance forever. However I decided to try it out and I think had it not been for Dr. Lehman being as awesome, knowledgable, caring, supportive and professional as he is, I would have changed my insurance and not thought twice. But after seeing him several times for injuries and being completely restored to brand new under his guidance, I can't see myself changing doctors as long as he is practicing. Just want to say thanks Doc I'm glad I found ya.

The doctor was curt, did not listen, started writing a prescription before even getting a feel for me. Her receptionists were unreliable, they put me on hold forever, told me the doctor would call me back and I never heard from her. I was prescribed an expensive medication that had no generic so I called to ask if I could have samples or a different medication. I left messages for two days, then I called again and was told "we have samples but have to get authorization from the Dr. to give them. She will call you". She NEVER CALLED. When I did get a call four days later, it was to reschedule my appointment! I told her I was not going to come in because I had been calling all week without ever hearing back and she kept saying she was going to charge me for the visit anyway. The place is unkempt, dirty, unorganized. There is no waiting room, just a chair in the hallway by the bathroom. A therapist sat with me for 45 minutes and was nice, but then the doctor came in and started writing my prescription after 2 minutes of being there, had no idea who I was or why I was there. SHe just seems interested in writing whatever medication and getting her money, she shows no interest in the patient.

My first time visiting this facility was in 2006 as I had a Kaiser medical plan under a previous employer. Since it was years ago, that visit was a blur if I can remember clearly. Between then and now, I was also switching back and forth from Kaiser to Sharp/Scripps as I had difficulties finding a doctor that fit my needs.Fast forward to 2014 and with a new employer, I'm happy to say that I finally found a doctor through the KP.org website that actually took the time to get to know me and my family/medical history during my first visit. Her office is located at this facility making this convenient for me as I live nearly 2-3 minutes away. Although I had been here years ago, things have definitely changed (for the better) as they have integrated "self check-in" booths on every floor so that you don't have to wait in line. My experience during my first visit was a breeze as I checked-in with one of their representatives on the first floor who then notified me after paying that I was all ready to go except that I needed to be on the third floor. It was during my second visit when I decided to use the self service check-in which I liked a lot since I wasn't in the mood to fall in line. After checking in, I only waited 5 minutes before being seen by a nurse. The nurse that dealt with me was very pleasant and cordial. After taking all my vitals, I informed her of what I was in for and she then led me to my room. Airy and clean, the room looked well kept and stocked by their staff. Within 5 minutes, I was seen by my doctor whom was like a breath of fresh air! Sweet, bubbly and very personable, I knew I chose the right fit once she took the time to get to know me as well as review my past record that started in 2006 with Kaiser. She was very honest which I was very much appreciative for. During my second visit which was a follow up, I made sure to ask plenty of questions even if it didn't relate to what I was originally being seen for and she was more than happy to share her opinions and suggestions without making me feel like I needed to leave in a rush.Since I will be on a physical therapy treatment, this facility will serve as my second home. So far I've had a pretty good experience as everything has been a breeze from checking-in to being seen as well as picking up my prescriptions. I'm happy to say that I will be keeping Kaiser under my medical plan as long as my doctor doesn't decide to leave and if I don't move to another neighborhood :)

Although I had been here years ago, things have definitely changed (for the better) as they have integrated "self check-in" booths on every floor so that you don't have to wait in line. My experience during my first visit was a breeze as I checked-in with one of their representatives on the first floor who then notified me after paying that I was all ready to go except that I needed to be on the third floor. It was during my second visit when I decided to use the self service check-in which I liked a lot since I wasn't in the mood to fall in line. After checking in, I only waited 5 minutes before being seen by a nurse. The nurse that dealt with me was very pleasant and cordial. After taking all my vitals, I informed her of what I was in for and she then led me to my room. Airy and clean, the room looked well kept and stocked by their staff. Within 5 minutes, I was seen by my doctor whom was like a breath of fresh air! Sweet, bubbly and very personable, I knew I chose the right fit once she took the time to get to know me as well as review my past record that started in 2006 with Kaiser. She was very honest which I was very much appreciative for. During my second visit which was a follow up, I made sure to ask plenty of questions even if it didn't relate to what I was originally being seen for and she was more than happy to share her opinions and suggestions without making me feel like I needed to leave in a rush.Since I will be on a physical therapy treatment, this facility will serve as my second home. So far I've had a pretty good experience as everything has been a breeze from checking-in to being seen as well as picking up my prescriptions. I'm happy to say that I will be keeping Kaiser under my medical plan as long as my doctor doesn't decide to leave and if I don't move to another neighborhood :)

I first went to Dr. Downie with what I thought was just another sinus infection, as I tend to get them two-three times a year, usually viral. I finally had decided it was time for an ENT and not just the urgent care. As time progressed under his care, antibiotics and steroids were not helping, a CT scan showed a deviated septum and how horribly my right side sinuses were doing. I had surgery in late July. After surgery, he told my husband that I had over two years of mucus built up and that no amount medicine or time would have cleared it. We had definitely made the right decision. Surgery went great as did my after care and recovery. I am one month post surgery now, and feel pretty great. I have days where I feel a little cruddy, but it is to be expected for a while after surgery as the sinuses need to "restart." I would recommend anyone to Dr. Downie.

Apparently, the "cautious approach" involved coughing up my copay for nothing!

I had surgery at Fountain Valley and I had a great expierence. I have to admit I work there so I was very comfortable choosing the hospital. I have been a cardiovascular nurse for over 20 years and have worked at most OC hospitals and felt the most comfortable with Fountain Valley. It's a positive sign when staff make the choice to use the hospital they work in. I am shocked at the horrible reviews listed. I have never searched Yelp before, rest assured our hospital looks at these and takes action. I won't make any excuses for the poor expierences people have had, I will tell you this...my insurance allows me to go anywhere I picked Fountain Valley because I know what it is ALL about. Great staff, doctors and good quality care. We have high tech equipment and trained staff that use it. I was kept comfortable, warm and felt really good about my stay. Dr. Guerrero did a great job on my surgery. My mom needs the same thing and when she goes she will be treated by him at Fountain Valley. Feed back is good keep posting, I will review these posts with my staff.

I am so grateful that I found Dr. Porter. I had severe neck pain especially when turning my head for months and couldn't find help. I had been to two orthopedic surgeons and despite MRI's they offered no hope. I also had been to a chiropractor, an acupuncturist, decompression therapy, physical therapy, and had submitted my MRI to another neurosurgeon who said he couldn't help me. After seeing my MRI and seeing me, Dr. Porter said maybe he could fuse C1&2. He did fuse them and my neck has been pain free for over two years. Since then he also fused four vertebrae in my lower back and now it is pain free. Dr. Porter is also very caring, will answer any questions, and even prays with patients before surgery. I highly recommend him.

Check-in staff for the various offices have always been top-notch as usual for KP as a whole. Given the volume of patients this complex treats, it runs smoothly, quietly, and essentially perfectly. Very impressive.

My daughter was 14-months old when our insurance switched to Kaiser Permanente. She had been having serious medical problems for 7-months and we'd been to countless specialists without any answers. We'd been dealing with a "normal" doctors office and the ball was dropped several times. There was no coordination of care (except for me), specialist reports to her doctor were going un-noticed, it was a terrible time for us. When we switched to KP and she started seeing Dr. Zilioli everything changed. All of the sudden communicating with her doctor and staff wasn't only easy, it was a pleasant experience! He listened to all my "Mom theories" and considered my thoughts when making decisions. He picked up the phone and CALLED some of the specialists she'd seen and asked them for their thoughts. She is 3.5 now and we're still very happy and continued to be amazed by KP's unique way of delivering health care with customer service. After experiencing the non-KP way and the KP-way I have to say that I'm in love with Kaiser Permanente and Dr. Zilioli. Now all I have to do is pray we don't have to switch insurance companies for the rest of my life!

High rating for Ease of appointment, Promptness, and Courteous staff, as those are indications of Kaiser being an excellent medical service. As far as everything else goes, Dr. Lee is one of the worst doctors I have experienced. His medical advice is such common knowledge that it feels as if he doesn't understand medicine. I.e. if you have bad heartburn his advice is don't eat spicy food. Can't sleep? Don't drink caffeine. Have depression? Do something that makes you happy. In other words, if you need serious medical help or feel that medication would be necessary in your case, then you need to switch doctors because I'm not sure if it will take multiple appointments to get what you need or what the deal is. He loves to shame me (and I'm assuming other patients) about my choices in life, instead of speaking about it like an adult. If you get Dr. Kyle Lee from Redlands Kaiser I highly advise you to switch as quickly as possible as I don't wish the same experience I've had on anyone else.

Dr. Theiss is very thorough in keeping track of the healing of my fractured femur, which has taken 4 years now to be (finally) almost totally healed. He calls up the radiologist while we are looking at my x-rays, and they compare them with the previous ones; this year the comparison was dramatic and we are so relieved to see that! He has given me good advice on rehabbing this fracture.

I had a dangerous case of pre eclampsia for TWO MONTHS that Khamvongsa ignored. He had so many c-sections/surgeries scheduled that he would spend an average of two minutes with me per visit. His nurse would also take my blood pressure 3or 4 times in various positions trying to get the lowet read for my chart instead of what i t actually was. HORRIBLE experience. My son could have died, I could have died. He grossly NEGLECTED us. I also had a horrific epesiotomy/tear with dozens of stitches that subsequently became infected. He NEVER gave me an internal (pre or post partem) I literally had to demand that he spend 5 minutes taking out my stitches. By the end of my pregnancy I had no respect and no trust in him...in fact I feared him. Do yourself a favor and find another practice.

I wish more doctors were like him and had the caring, compassionate heart that still want to help people get better! I will ALWAYS be a loyal patient of his!

I've been coming to the Vista Kaiser since I was 18. I was recently reading news articles about Kaisers psychiatry department and the issues that had been uncovered in 2014, so it got me thinking about my long list of experiences here. I've seen a total of 4 therapists, 1 psychologist and 2 psychiatrists here. I've only had a problem with 2 of my therapists, simply because we just didn't click, but the rest of the doctors and therapists are great. The worst part of Kaiser, not only in psychiatry but in almost every department, is the long wait times in between available appointments. I typically need to wait about 3 weeks to make an appointment in psych, which is why I highly recommend making 2 or 3 appointments at once. They also have limited hours available which is inconvenient for people who aren't able to get work off for appointments. Beyond this issue there are tons of dedicated and genuinely thoughtful and caring staff who really do try and listen to you. Also, the pharmacy at Vista is so much better than San Marcos. I usually only have to wait 10 minutes to pick up my prescriptions whereas at San Marcos it can take up to 2 hours. Kaiser really is a place who cares for their patients, although it's inevitable people may believe otherwise. I'm not sure I can say it's the best, but when it comes to the Vista location I can honestly say I have much more positive to say than negative.

My whole family goes to Dr. Rizkallah at Kaiser Permanente. Frankley, he is the ONLY reason we stay with Kaiser. He is caring, not affraid to order blood work on an annual bases "just to make sure everything is normal" and will order a CT or MRI when needed without batting an eye. It is because of his caring nature and willingness to do his job effectively that we found out my son had fluid in the brain. Dr. Rizkallah got us to a NeuroSurgeon before my son had could have a hemmorage. After years of taking my son to a doctor for his horrible headaches, (at least 10) finally a doctor was willing to order a CT scan which revealed the real reason. No... it wasn't allergies like I was told all those years. Thanks Dr. Rizkallah for saving my son's life. You are truly the best there is.

I was referred to Dr Canales when I was diagnosed with Cushing's Disease and a pituitary tumor. He is compassionate and has a positive attitude. He is very knowledgable about Cushing's, which is rare for most Endocrinologists. He explains things well. He answers my emails within a few hours. His staff has told me that he is the Endocrinologist that listens to the patients the most and he will not hesitate to order testing needed to clarify what is wrong with the patient. The only complaint I have is I had requested to see a Endo for years. My PCP stated the Endocrinology staff reviewed my info and said I did not need to see a Endo because my PCP could handle my issues, which was not true at all.

Battling a three week long virus was bad enough but this Dr could not have acted more annoyed or accusatory that he saw me repeatedly. I had a terrible cough and when asking him to refill my cough syrup one time he treated me as if I was a common criminal trying to get drugs! He was condescending and made a point to embarrass me. I have never been treated so poorly by a Dr. Then he told me not to come back and to see a specialist as something must be seriously wrong with me if I had been sick for going on three weeks. I told him my whole office was in the same state, it was not just me. Then he started making wild guesses saying it must be acid reflux that was causing the nasal drip and cough. Totally ridiculous. Stay away!

People have very strong opinions about Kaiser Permanente. I honestly wouldn't have chosen them as my insurance plan, but it's all my work offers. I really, truly lucked out with my doctor, Dr. Daniel Jones at the Englewood location. I'd highly recommend him to anyone who uses Kaiser. First and foremost, he has always been on time or early for every appointment I've had with him. He's very kind, knowledgeable, and approachable. One other great feature Kaiser has now is the ability to email your doctor via their website. I've actually saved trips and additional co-payments by emailing him to ask questions and get prescriptions refilled and he's always responded on the same day.

i was seeing this psychiatrist for around 6 months and from moment one, it was pretty much a disaster. in the first session, i sat there and gave a detailed history. at the end of it, she looked up and made a statement about what i'd just said that had absolutely NOTHING to do with anything i'd just said. she was also petulant and short - one time i was in the office and the bathroom code wasn't working. she became very snippy and childish with me - explaining i had to be wrong since she'd just used the bathroom. turns out i was completely right. i wouldn't recommend this therapist to ANYONE - not even to one of my pets.

Do not waste time here. You are better off going to see PA at a CVS or Walgreens. Unethical, immoral and most likely illegal. When your blood is used for testing, you have the right to know what test are for and not to be lied to. David Saltin called my wife delusional and raised his voice, in the most unacceptable manner, all within the first 3, yes 3 minutes that he was in her room. It is below anyones level of humanity to be so rude and unprofessional to someone is sick. Then 4 hours in ER and not a nurse, not a doctor or anyone, except the lab girl came in to draw labs but no one came to check on her. We were there because , after having a seizure earlier in the week, she had the same euphoric feeling today. Our doctor sent us there. We waited in the lobby for 2 hours and when we went back we were put in a room that had been empty. The triage nurse didn't even push the wheelchair back. I would love to have a job where it didn't matter how badly you treated people. No, I would not, I have too much respect for myself and others after serving 15 years as a Marines, I think that I have earned and deserve a little back. Vets you will get better service at the V.A. Medical Center. .

He performed a hernia repair on me which seems to have been successful. My main issue is with the anesthesia doc (Elizabeth Nesbitt)who did an end run around me in order to impose Versed - and Dr. Moazzez' attitude towards my (bad) experience with same. I reacted badly to the Versed and ended up having general anesthesia, which I specifically said I wanted to avoid. When I complained to Dr. Moazzez about this, his feeble reply was "We're always ready to use general when using MAC".(MAC=Monitored Anesthetic Care). All this means is they will hit you with Versed and hope nothing goes wrong. There are firetrucks at the airport too, but you hope you never have to use them. Also on the day of surgery, both docs seemed to have an attitude. I am not happy with the anesthesia and I find both of the doctors' attitudes towards me to be uncaring and unprofessional. While he may be competent, I will choose another surgeon in the future if I should need one.

I'm a 43-year-old man with good muscle development who has always exercised. However, I put on abdominal and back fat during two years of overseeing home renovations. (I bought lunch for the contractors, and ate it too. Bad move.) And, along the way, fat also accumulated under my chin. I knew that at my age, there was no way of losing the fat without going on a crazy diet, which would also take off muscle. So, I decided to look into liposuction. After months of research, one plastic surgeon topped my list: Dr. Glat. He has worked on many men, which isn't the case for most plastic surgeons. He is also Board Certified in Plastic Surgery (certificationmatters website). (Do not go to a plastic surgeon who is not certified in Plastic Surgery. Some are certified in something else, or not at all. If they don't bother to uphold the high standards of board certification, what does that say about them and how you'll be treated?) I met Dr. Glat and was very impressed. He respectfully answered all my questions (even the silly ones), took a lot of time evaluating my concerns, and was straightforward regarding my expected outcome. Also, his office assistant Andrea was so helpful, and worked to get me set up with financing and a surgery date. She made sure I understood the procedure and what to expect during the weeks to follow. The surgery went very well, and aside from bruises that disappeared surprisingly quickly, I felt good overall. All of my questions during post-op were immediately answered, which helped me understand the completely natural process of healing. Now, I look - and feel - better than I can remember. My chin fat is gone, which took a decade off my face. Truly remarkable. My body fat went from 21% to 18% and I lost a full inch off my waist. I no longer have this fatty gut hanging over my shorts, and I feel like "me" again. This decision was one of the best I've made: I have new motivation to work out, because I want to stay this way. It's like being given a second chance. I'm also watching my diet much more because I would like to "protect my investment" for as long as possible. Overall, I just feel better about myself. As a result, I strongly recommend Dr. Glat. He is honest and incredibly skilled. Plastic surgery is an art and a science, and he is a master of both. I couldn't be happier with my result, which has changed my life more than I could have imagined.

Since I consider excellent medical care a very important part of life, I joined Dr. Bell's Concierge Choice program. I can say, without hesitation, that I would not have spent the annual fee to join the Program if I didn't consider Dr. Bell an experienced and knowledgeable physician. If you are seeking a first class physician, I highly recommend Dr. Scott Bell.........in fact, I am recommending him to my daughter and son-in-law!

I was referred to Dr.Suppiah by my doctor. I regret making an appointment judging by the online reviews. I figured it couldn't be that bad, I was wrong. I was going to make an appointment with another doctor but the wait was 3-4 months long. The office is cramped and hot. I had to wait 45 minutes after my original appointment time to finally be seen. Once I got to see the doctor she flew my examination, asking me questions rapid fire. I felt like I was being rushed and I was in and out less than 15 minutes. I'm pretty sure 1st time patients require more time to be seen but I'm just a number in her mind. I still had no idea what was wrong with me. 2 months went by and I never heard from Dr.Suppiah about the blood tests I had done. I finally received an unprofessional looking bill from the office stating I hadn't paid my copay. Luckily that was cleared up easily with no problems. Dr.Suppiah had the receptionist on the phone give me my lab results. I'm pretty sure that its against the law. I still have no clue what is wrong with me or if I need to go see another doctor. I'm glad I kept my appointment with the other office. I'm sure it will be worth the wait. Find another doctor, don't waste your time especially if its something life threatening.

I am one of Dr. Anne White's nurses. I have worked for her now for many years. She is one of the most honest, level-headed doctors I have ever had the pleasure to know. She teaches her staff to go by the golden rule, ""Do unto others as you would have them do unto you."" Hearing her say the golden rule followed by...and you won't go wrong, is permanently etched into my brain. She believes it and she leads by example. She is a talented educator and has a gift of putting medical terminology into laymens terms. She spends a lot of time educating her patients and hosts a radio show on WSJS called ""Dare to be beautiful"" in order to get the word out to the community about our procedures. She has her person email address printed on the front of our appointment/business cards. Before every new patient leaves she asks them if she has answered all of their questions. She also points out her email address on the business card and asks them to email her if they think of any question they forgot to ask when they get home. Dr. White is kind, a gifted communicator, and the most honest, available doctor I have ever known. If you chose to come and see us, I promise you, you will not be disappointed.
