Who would want to hold a sick 20 month old!? His job is to stay well so he doesn't get other children sick, not to mention he has a family of his own. I think the point of a Doctor is to prevent illness and heal the sick. It sounds like he was taking necessary precautions to do so. Dr. Sonnen is awesome. When I first started taking my children to him 4 years ago, I lived twenty minutes from his office. I now live about an hour and a half away, and I refuse to switch Dr's. My children have health issues, so this is not a yearly visit that I drive an hour and a half for, but more of a biweekly trip. It is well worth it. His staff of nurses are caring, the front office staff knows who I am when I walk in the door. When I have a question and I call Dr. Sonnen's nurse line, someone always calls me back within half an hour, and it is not uncommon for Dr. Sonnen to call me back himself, if my child's issue is important. I have received a follow-up call from him on a SATURDAY to check

I have been seeing Dr. Tin for almost 3 years. I am a chronic pain patient. I have been on a series of pain reducing drugs over this course of time. Dr. Tin is a soft spoken and kind doctor, but he is very strict. He only gives the smallest amount of med he needs to to help his patient and questions you if you are having increased pain. Recently I hit a wall with the same regimen I've been on for 2.5 years and asked to maybe change off of a drug that has too much Tylenol in it... To which he told me he's comfortable with the amount I am ingesting. I called to ask kaiser what my options are and they automatically filed a "report". I believe most of the issues you will face at kaiser will not be due to Dr. Tin, but due to Kaiser being a sub-par medical group.

This Doctor is out of touch with the times and with her responsibility as a Pediatrician. I spent 45 minutes waiting in a 10x10 box. I said she was offending me and had she ran on time we would have been a little more compliant. She contunied to lecture me at shiwhc time I asked her to stop and she still continued. She is extreemly offensive and comes across as being better than everyone else. She also told me children should NEVER have snacks and simply three meals a day. a one year old and four year old can not eat at 11am and wait till 5:30 pm for dinner. She is not encouraging to parents, she belittles you rather than sympathize with you and she is intolerant of children's behaviors (unless they sit quietly in a chair waiting on her for two hours).

Dr. Bergman is a wonderful and caring doctor. I left an office that had 12 pediatricians on rotation and my children never saw the same doctor twice. When my children see doctor Bergman he knows them and their medical history. Our appointments are never rushed and he is more than glad to answer any questions and address any concerns we might have. He is not quick to write a prescription and send us on our way, but rather get to the root of the problem and always follows up with us. We never have to wait more than 10 minutes for our appointment and his staff is efficient and knowledgeable. We have been going to his office for 2 years and my only regret is not switching to his practice sooner.

I was a long-time patient of Dr. Clever who I was rate as perhaps the best physician I have ever had. I was certainly concerned when he retired and Dr. Sherman took over his practice. I have been extermely pleased with her, however. She seems truly to care about me. When I reported an occassional irregular heart beat during an annual physical, she sent me for a stress test, reported back to me on the test and worked with me to find a medication to deal with the problem. I find her friendly and easy to talk with. I miss Dr. Clever but also will miss Dr. Sherman now that Bay Internal Medicine is closing.

Dr. Trager is one of the good guys. My very favorite physician. His practice us unusual, as he is both a pediatrician and a dermatologist. He has been my dermatologist for years. Before I found Dr. Trager, I had been to other dermatologists, experiencing extensive waiting time to be seen, and having my questions and concerns sometimes dismissed as unimportant. Dr. Trager's office is well managed, with waits kept to a minimum. But even more important, he really listens. I understand that skin issues can be difficult to diagnose, and have experienced a trial-and-error approach with other dermatologists. However, Dr. Trager tends to "get it right" the first time. Both of my children are his patients, and he has a wonderful manner with teenagers. So rare to find a talented doctor with a bedside manner that works well with both adults and children. I unequivocally recommend Jonathan Trager.

Literally the WORST customer service I have ever experienced. Although I'm all for judging a hospital based on medical services, I have been unable to even obtain these due to the idiotic advice nurses that block patient's access to appointments like feral monkeys.The first time I called to make an appointment was last fall. I had a fever of 102 while on medication, severe congestion, a cough, and a throat so sore that I spoke in a raspy whisper. After putting me on hold and transferring me so many times that I became fatigued and almost passed out, I was finally passed off to an advice nurse who refused multiple times to book me an appointment or even a strep test. My friend suggested it might be because I have insurance and so they can't bankrupt me as they would like to do. I am inclined to agree. I ended up not seeing a doctor at all and having an on and off fever for the next week and half and a cough for another month.The second, and LAST time I will ever be dealing with the kaiser appointment system is today. I called in for an appointment because I sprained my ankle two days before and had been experiencing increased swelling and numbness from my calf to my toes. I was transferred to an advice nurse who, I kid you not, spoke exactly like Miss Swan. Not only was she impossible to understand, but she was also highly incompetent. Although she agreed that I should get an x-ray ASAP, she was unable to figure out if the Davis location had a radiologist on site (what kind of hospital is unequipped for x-rays?!) and put me on hold for five minutes as she tried to find out. She wasn't able to, and suggested that I drive to the Sacramento location for urgent care. This is after I told her that my RIGHT ankle was the one that was injured. I declined, and she insisted, and then I asked for an appointment in Davis, and she declined, and I hung up. And now I will be shredding my kaiser card into itty bitty pieces and stuffing them down the gutter.

I traveled from Virginia to Ft. Lauderdale's Holy Cross Hospital because I had heard such wonderful things about Dr. Gates...and they were all true. Even other doctors highly recommend him. I had both polycystic ovaries (along with a portion of my sigmoid colon removed) laporascopically, and all I have is a 1" scar beside my belly-button! I have referred friends to Dr. Weiner and have heard good reviews later. I feel confident referring her because I have been to her over 10 years with a host of complaints from skin issues, mental health concerns, chest pain, high blood pressure, etc. I had one very bad spell recently where she immediately sent me to the ER even though I tried to talk her out of it and she was right to send me. Get to know Dr. Weiner and you'll find that she is a good mom, empathic listener and an astute, intuitive physician. Dr. Tierney is an absolute gem of a doctor. We are forever grateful for the tender care and sweetness he has shown our daughter for the first year of her life. Never condescending and full of quiet humor, Dr. Tierney is always at the ready to patiently answer a new parent's questions that range from the absurd to more profound concerns. His sensibilities and kindness are refreshing as we try to navigate the terrain of parenting. Never dismissive and ever steady, we always look forward to seeing him and value his advice and huge heart. Once you see how he speaks to your dear babe or asks how you're doing, you will feel it. Some docs are aces on the mound.

Dr. Flanum was incredibly unprofessional. Going to see him wasted 3 hours out of my work day for him to tell me that he couldn't find anything wrong.I waited for 2 hours to see him. It's a good thing I brought a book. He asked me a few questions, quickly looked at my x-rays and walked out of the room. I could hear him telling jokes to a coworker in the hall after he said goodbye when he left me sitting (on crutches) in the exam room. He didn't tell me that I was done, that I could leave, OR how to get out of the office. I had to walk out and ask him if I was free to go... and wandered through the halls till I found the check-out desk.I will NEVER return to OPA. They may look good on the outside, but the entire operation seems like a complete joke (which is also their reputation in the medical community around Anchorage).

The surgical removal went well (despite a minor complication), and will only leave the tiniest scar (which I greatly prefer over a huge, annoying lump). The nurse gave thorough after-care instructions, and it's healing nicely.I've noticed that the other 2 reviews said he seemed a bit brusque, but I did not find that to be the case. I like that he was very frank, honest, and open with me about the whole thing, even letting me see what had been removed (which I thought was kinda cool). I like that he didn't waste time with any sugar-coated explanations! What I needed was a skilled dermatologist/surgeon, and that's what I got!

Dr Caplan was my Dr with my second daughter!!! from the start her and i really clicked!! i had a difficult delivery with my first daughter (ended in an emergency csection bc i had been in active labor for like 15 hours and didnt know it and was not dilating and she was in distress) Dr Caplan and i came up with a plan so that i wouldnt have a rushed emergency situation again!! i had issues my whole pregnancy with vaginal bleeding and every time i started bleeding i would call and they would get me in right away!! and after my appt i would usually be sent for an ultrasound to make sure she was okay and everything was great! at 36 weeks i had my normal appt and everything was great (or so we thought) her heart rate was 148 and i was measuring good so we thought everything was fine! i had been having a little back pain so she sent me for a non stress test to make sure i wasnt contracting (i had back labor with my first) just to make sure we didnt need to change the date of my repeat csection! and when we got up for my test we were having a hard time getting her heart rate on the monitor (nothing new she hate those things and usually hides back by my spine!) well after an ultrasound we found out we lost her! Dr Caplan was crushed!!! she clear her schedule for the day and didnt leave my side!!! she made sure i have all the information i needed to make the best decisions about everything!!! when i went in for my csection she help my hand and rubbed my hair and told me to just cry and talked to me until i was under! she sent my placenta off to try and get as much info as possible!!! we found out my placenta had clotted (placental abruption or so we thought) and after i was release her and her staff call me at least once a week to see how we were doing! and she ran a ton of test to get as many answers as we could!! and come to find out i have a genetic gene mutation called MTHFR (which is not usually tested for unless the mother has had many pregnancy loses!) after seeing a specialist he told me he had no idea why Dr Caplan tested for it most doctors wouldnt! I AM SO GREATFUL THAT SHE DID!! she has been there for us every step of the way! its been 12 weeks since our angel grew her wings and i honestly do not think we could have gotten through this without Dr Caplan and her staff!!! I will never see another Dr!!!

First of all i am completely shocked to see all the positive remarks on this doctor. I am her patient and i am expecting my first child. On my first appointment, she seemed to be okay;she ordered few lab work and also asked me to go for the screening (NT SCAN). On my second visit, it was so obvious that she didnt even study my case/ my lab result. All she did was, taking a listen to baby's heart beat and said everything was normal. She was hurrying and didn't bother to sit and listen to my doubts. One thing i noticed, whenever she communicate, she so fast and never bother whether we understood her or not. Come on, this is my first pregnancy! On my second appointment, i requested a copy of all my screening and lab results, so she made a copy and gave it to me. I came home and i went through by myself with the help of google. I notice there were some issues with my report that this doctor never bother to tell me and i am pretty sure she herself is not aware of it because she didnt do her homework before seeing me. How ridiculous it that!!!!!!!!!!! I was already having pain and other complication due to the problem i had so on my 3'rd appointment with her, i asked her 'how come you didnt tell me anything about it?' She was shocked and took my report, and only then she noticed the problem being written in that report. Then she immediately tried to pretend saying ' ohhhh, dont worry, this is nothing...bla bla' Come on, think about it!! Is she really being caring and responsible here? Honestly i dont think so. She just wants a lot patient!!!!!!! I am totally not happy with this dr, so i have decided to switch to another ob dr. Be careful people, dont just rely on this review. If you ask me, i will not recommend her at all to any of my friends/family. Totally disappointing!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

My daughter was taken to Arrowhead Hospital on 11/26/11 by the Peoria Fire Dept after passing out 2 differnt times, hitting her head, throwing up, and shaking and wetting her pants. Her nurse was so rude to her and my wife and I. Her bed side manner was so far off base. The so called P.A. that was taking care of her seemed like she did NOT care or want to take the time out to figured out what was really going on with her. I would have rather had a vet take care of my daughter then this so called P.A. who spent a total of 10 mins with her. All she did was order a number of labs to be done then after they were done she came in said everything came back okay and said "Some people just pass out for no real reason its nothing to worry about just go home a rest." This was the first time she even saw her. She just did not want to take the time out to figure out what could be going on. Trust me I would not take a frog there for a Band-Aid. I hope this is helpful and hope you are all in good health. Brian

One and done new patient here! I went to see Dr. Kimber after having a miscarriage. I was cramping and in pain for over a week. I wanted to make sure everything had turned out okay. I also needed leave paperwork filled out and signed. My company documents any major medical issues and absences. They needed a VERY simple piece of paper filled out and she straight up REFUSED. After I confronted her about the paperwork, she rushed through my exam, told me to get dressed and then literally explained to me where the exit door was. She never said goodbye, never explained what she saw in my exam and never showed her face to me again. I've never been treated like this by a doctor.. The funny thing is, I really liked her before I asked about the paperwork. She was kind and personable. Now I know it was all a front. She makes a lot of money off of her patients. Don't ever expect her to have your back, because she won't!

Dr. Brown and staff are everything people look for in a medical practice.  I experienced literally no wait time for my office visit or procedure.  They are very professional and courteous.  He answere                    d all my questions.  Dianna pointed me to his website with even more info and videos.  I was very impressed with the videos which greatly helped reduce my level of apprehension about the colonoscopy.  Having completed one now, I honestly don't see what many people make out to be so dreadful about it.  Most people would say that it really wasn't the procedure itself (I hope not since you are sedated), but the prep.  I used the MoviPrep as prescribed and added some flavoring.  It doesn't taste terrific, but it's definitely drinkable and has the desired outcome.  After the procedure itself, I felt completely fine.  I had absolutely zero nausea, bloating or discomfort.  I went home and wallpapered actually! It's not that bad at all and well worth the peace of mind.

I went to Dr. Kieserman because I was dealing with a cold/fluid in my right ear which was plugged up. I have to say my initial impression of the office wasn't the greatest and it went downhill as the appointment progressed with true dissatisfaction the result of doctors actions or should I say lack of action. As I mentioned, the initial impression wasn't good. The bench that substituted as a coffee table in the center of waiting room was VERY dusty. Really not cool for a doctor's office with patients who suffer from allergies (or really any doctors office for that matter.) And it wasn't one or two days of dust. It was definitely in the crevices of the wood furniture for some time. Next before I was brought into see the doctor I was given a piece of paper that spelled out what constituted as a medical procedure above and beyond the office visit. If the doctor looked up my nose or down my throat with a special scope it would be deemed a surgical procedure by the health insurance company. Code for not covered by your insurance and this is going to cost you money so be prepared. When I got into the exam room with the doctor he didn't even look into my ear or up my nose before he said he'd have to do a earring test and some other test. Excuse me why are you jumping to the need to do an ear test before you have even done a general exam of the patient. It CLEARLY became evident that the doctor was looking to do things that added cost.  Finally I was like 'aren't you even going to look into my ear?' which I think temporarily guilt'd him into it. He wouldn't give me any indication what was wrong with me other than I had an infection in my ear and that it could be something other than a common cold causing it but he couldn't tell without doing these additional test. He positioned it as I really needed these test to know what is going on.  Good grief I had a cold with fluid in my ear and I needed an antibiotic not a bunch of test that garnered this man more money.  The best way I can describe this guy is SHYSTER.  His letterhead has, Steve Kieserman, MD, LLP. I don't know if I have ever seen a doctors office with LLP on their letterhead.  Please do yourself a favor and find another doctor.

As I mentioned, the initial impression wasn't good. The bench that substituted as a coffee table in the center of waiting room was VERY dusty. Really not cool for a doctor's office with patients who suffer from allergies (or really any doctors office for that matter.) And it wasn't one or two days of dust. It was definitely in the crevices of the wood furniture for some time. Next before I was brought into see the doctor I was given a piece of paper that spelled out what constituted as a medical procedure above and beyond the office visit. If the doctor looked up my nose or down my throat with a special scope it would be deemed a surgical procedure by the health insurance company. Code for not covered by your insurance and this is going to cost you money so be prepared. When I got into the exam room with the doctor he didn't even look into my ear or up my nose before he said he'd have to do a earring test and some other test. Excuse me why are you jumping to the need to do an ear test before you have even done a general exam of the patient. It CLEARLY became evident that the doctor was looking to do things that added cost.  Finally I was like 'aren't you even going to look into my ear?' which I think temporarily guilt'd him into it. He wouldn't give me any indication what was wrong with me other than I had an infection in my ear and that it could be something other than a common cold causing it but he couldn't tell without doing these additional test. He positioned it as I really needed these test to know what is going on.  Good grief I had a cold with fluid in my ear and I needed an antibiotic not a bunch of test that garnered this man more money.  The best way I can describe this guy is SHYSTER.  His letterhead has, Steve Kieserman, MD, LLP. I don't know if I have ever seen a doctors office with LLP on their letterhead.  Please do yourself a favor and find another doctor.

She was also able to diagnose a potentially life threatening heart murmur on my younger daughter and her lactose intolerance when she was almost two years old. I saw her on an emergency basis, and she was a life savior. I was very upset to know that my two year old's insurance approved pediatrician had never diagnosed my daughter. I switched insurance companies to have Dr. Fein be my daughter's doctor. She is worth it.

I had a terrible experience with Dr. Benoit. I went to him for first trimester screening after being referred by my OB. Being my first pregnancy I was unsure what to expect. I thought everything was going smoothly, we were watching the ultrasound of the baby on the TV screen. While I was still in a state of undress from the exam, Dr. Benoit tells us that the baby has a neural tube defect, and is non-viable. I began to cry, and Dr. Benoit left the room. I got dressed and one of his nurses ushered us into a conference room, where I was given a print out of information on the neural tube defect. Dr. Benoit went to see other patients. I was so upset I wanted to leave immediately.. I was told that I could call the office if I had further questions, but when I called I had to leave a message and never received a call back. I would advise expectant mothers to avoid Dr. Benoit, as this was an experience I never want anyone else to ever have to go through!

If you are looking for a nice, caring and a brilliant gynecologist, Dr. Tran is your answer.

Bad, uncaring doctor. Please stay away. I came to see Dr. Carreon for my annual check-up and some pain that I was feeling in my ab. I waited about 45mins before I was let in to see her, and then she spent less than 5mins with me. I was a new patient, so you would assume that there is a lot to learn about me, but she came into the room, and barely asked me any questions. She barely even touched my ab to see what the issue was. All she did was told me to get some blood work, to see what the issue was. I don't even understand what the purpose of me being there was for. Since she barely even looked at me, all this could have been done over the phone. Then later, after I got my bill for almost $250 for 5mins, I called to discuss the bill, and the staff was not helpful or responsive. After about 4 conversations w/ the staff, I asked to speak w/ Dr. Carreon personally, so that I can solve the problem quicker. Can you believe what her staff told me? "The doctor will not speak to patients over the phone. She will only talk to you if you are in the office". What type of doctor is this??? I've had many other doctors during my 30 or so years, and a GOOD doctor would always take time to speak w/ a patient, especially if they had a question or concern. Dr. Carreon's time however is so "valuable" that she is unwilling to spend even a couple mins on the phone w/ me to clarify this issue. Again, another example of a BAD doctor. From all these examples, all I can say is that Dr. Carreon is a doctor who only cares about money, which is proven by her unwillingness to talk w/ you unless you are in her office, and she can bill you for her time. She is a uncaring, money hungry doctor. STAY AWAY!

I've been seen by many doctors, but Dr. Ryan is far and away the best primary care physician I have ever had. He has been my primary care doctor for at least 15 years, and in all that time I've never had a bad experience with him. He is extremely intelligent. He takes the time necessary to listen to you. He explains things in detail. He gladly answers all of your questions. He doesn't rush you out the door like many doctors do these days. He also is up-to-date in his knowledge. He contacts you after visits to let you know what's going on with lab results, x-rays, etc. and to check on you, as appropriate. He is also extremely pleasant during visits. As far as I'm concerned, he's everything a caring doctor should be. I hope he never leaves Kaiser. If he does, I'll change health plans to keep him as my primary doctor. As for waits, his thoroughness with patients sometimes causes him to exceed Kaiser's time allotment for each patient, but waiting for him is a small price to pay, given the outstanding care he provides.

Doctor Levine is a fantastic. I am so lucky to have found him to deliver my first baby. This is not your typical "baby factory". When I had my first appointment we sat in his office before he examined me to ask me what I was looking for and my expectations. I remember telling my friends this and they couldn't believe it. They said all of their doctors would meet with them for 5 minutes after waiting for an hour in the waiting area. This was not the case. You never wait more than 5 minutes to be seen by the doctor. He was always available and understood this was my first pregnancy. Whether you call during office hours or after office hours he always calls right back. Doctor Levine also respects your wishes. Absent a medical emergency he really respects what you want your birth to look like. He gives you his honest medical opinion and let's you make educated decisions about your birth. His after care is fantastic also! I ended up having a c section and it could not have gone better.

I saw Dr. Ratcliff after I broke my foot in July. I was prepared for the worst in terms of pain and a long recovery period. But after surgery and a tremendous amount of professional attention from him, I am actually walking on my own two feet in less than three months. And I have had minimal discomfort during the entire process. Both my feet may actually be in better condition now, thanks to his rational approach to treatment; and I am sure he has saved me money in his recommendations on shoes, shoe inserts, etc. I found his manner to be extraordinary down to earth and attentive.

I do believe I said until these experiences I personally had for the most part had ok experiences with kaiser until my daughter and mother actually had problems with the care and it went from bad to worse, life threatening caused by the physician and other providers. The ones of you who've had good care count yourself lucky, you're seeing the good doctors they actually have, the problem with that they get their experience at kaiser then move on to private practice and leave you with the worse of the worse and then that's when mistakes happen and the doctors and the nurses cover for each others mistakes. And I perfectly understand the system since I worked in the medical field myself for 15 years, so I know what a joke some of these care providers can be. And to the person who said it's a good place to work, I'm sure it is as long as you don't have a problem with them. But get treated by one of the bad providers there and lets see how long you like working there. I say choose any doctor HMO/PPO with caution, because it's the rare provider who really cares about what he or she is doing and who will admit to a mistake or not really knowing what's going on with your health. I reported this hospital and the doctors who were negligent in care to the medical board, that's how serious the problems was and is. Not something to take lightly, so the next patient hopefully will check their doctor out and know what skill or care the provider lacks.

Unlike other posts on here I'm not sure about the second negative one but the first not revealing her name only sane Jane Doe, I find Dr. Mark Flanum to be an excellent doctor, surgeon and person. I have been to just about every back specialist in Anchorage all to no avail. I had amazing experience with OPA as I had both hips replaced by Dr. Timothy Kavanaugh. I asked him for a recommendation and he recommended Dr. Flanum. I made an appointment and took my massive amounts of MRIs and x-rays and made an appointment my appointment time was at 2:30 by 2:40 I was in his office. His medical assistant Nicole was very friendly asked me all the pertinent questions and within minutes the doctor himself was in the examination room. He looked at the images that I gave him he ordered a couple x-rays which were taken immediately and we discussed several options he was not one to jump into surgery and therefore I received an injection which did not work. It only gave me about a month of relief. I made another appointment and again no wait and welcomed by a friendly staff and the option of surgery was disgusted me and with the images on the screen in detail he went over exactly what he was going to do. I felt very confident and decided to proceed with surgery. The day of the surgery he came into the waiting area and discussed everything that was going to be done with me again and was there in the recovery room when I woke up several hours later. I was equestrian for many years and that entails many years of falling off of horses when you ride jumpers that's part of the plan. I started having problems again and he immediately made an appointment this time with his PA, Michael. Again I had no waiting time I had met Michael before after my surgery and he discussed what he thought was going on. Dr. Flanum was there and apparently Michael had seen something that he wanted to speak with Dr. Flanum about. The two of them came back and pointed out that I had a synovial cyst that the facet joint was pressing on and it was interned pressing on the nerve which was causing my pain this doctor not one to jump as surgery is the only recourse or remedy suggested a procedure which I'm about to have done where they're going to attempt to pop the synovial cyst to see if that will relieve the pressure and the pain. He describes the procedure in detail and I feel so comfortable with this man. I highly recommend this doctor as he is a hands on doctor and for me has been very open with my treatment and all procedures I've had. FIVE STARS DR. FLANUM!!!

I trusted Dr. McLemore too much. I signed too many forms and gave her too much discretion. She talks in jargon and is impatient with questions. Going into the surgery, I did not expect her to do what she did. I have never signed so many legal forms going into an operation. I should have known something was wrong because I had to sign so many forms immediately before the operation.McLemore waited until just before I was under anesthesia to tell me the details about the surgery and she was impatient when I began to ask questions. I remember her walking out of the office on 3 occasions with some of my questions left unanswered. It's like she sets aside 5-10 minutes and when the time is up, she runs out of the office.I believe McLemore went overboard and destroyed more healthy tissue than was professionally appropriate. She left me in uncontrollable pain and it took me twice as long to heal as she told me it would. She was cold and unsympathetic toward me when I was in pain and distraught. When I expressed my concerns after the surgery she said I was a risk to her practice and advised me to find another surgeon. I felt like she turned against me because things didn't go well with my surgery. I've never had a really bad experience from surgery except with McLemore. I have asked for a review of my case because I think she made some professionally inappropriate decisions during the operation.

Dr. Jobman is WONDERFUL. She really took time to listen to me and gave me a lot of options. We discussed medications, medication, diet, everything that might help my issues, and she asked me how I wanted to proceed. She let me make decisions about my health. Best of all, when I walked in and told her what my problem was (anxiety and sleep) she did NOT say, "Lose weight and that will stop happening," like my last doctor did when I went to him for anything from an allergic reaction to a sore throat. Dr. Jobman didn't once bring up my weight, but when I said I wanted to lose some she have me lots of options for that, too. If you want a doctor who listens to you, works with you, and is both kind and knowledgeable, Dr. Jobman is right for you.

My husband had been very ill with an extended hospital stay. The discharge papers said to contact your primary care doctor after discharge...so we did. I understand if you don't know, but how about I will try to find out? Absolutely not! He even told me I was asking too many questions! Honestly, I was scared to death & worried about my husband. If we had not mentioned a referral to a specialist, he would have never offered. I really could go on but am I am just too exhausted from this whole ordeal!

Dr. Murphy has been kind, compassionate, patient, and above all, knowledgeable. He has something that a lot of pediatricians don't have-decades of experience. He has always been swift to respond, and always puts my child's health and safety before everything else. Though at times the office is busy, it really only affects the visit if you schedule at the last minute. If you can schedule in advance, and ask for the least busy time, it helps immensely. However, they always squeeze us in for an emergency. The staff is kind and helpful, the office is clean and cheerful, (and they just redid the place, including the murals, which really look great). They even have a kid's bathroom with a kid-sized toilet and a low sink, which always makes my younger kids feel very special, since it's "just their size". The nurses are very helpful, they are really thoughtful about the children, they answer questions intelligently, they try to make things fun, and (most importantly to many parents) they give shots kindly and quickly. Their office always has the vaccines we need, and have they are not forceful or intolerant of parents who opt for a slower vaccine schedule. Dr. Murphy does have a lot of patients, but he's popular because he's so good. My whole family will be heartbroken when our kids age out of this fantastic pediatrician.

I saw Dr. Paulos for the constant knee pain I was experiencing during my trail runs. After a long and thorough appointment including xrays and multiple hands-on tests, he sat down with me and took the time to explain EXACTLY what was going on with my knees and what my options were to fix them. I was expecting him to recommend surgery because he was a surgeon but instead he said he wanted to avoid that and would only cut as a last resort. I was so impressed by his commitment to natural healing and prevention and never once felt any pressure to get surgery. Durante did a tonsillectomy/adenoidectomy to cure my husband's sore throat/heartburn/canker sore issues. When Durante called for a post-surgery follow up, my hus asked me to talk because it hurt a lot to talk. Durante REFUSED to speak to me on the phone, although my hus was next to me, saying "it doesn't hurt that bad, put him on the phone." Shortly after surgery, my hus became ill with ulcerative pharyngitis (canker sores down his throat). Durante did a culture on a TUESDAY & gave penicillin to hopefully cure it. By Friday, my hus couldn't even swallow WATER, but we never heard from the doc, so he called the office. After making him drive there, Durante said "No wonder why penicillin wasn't working, you have staph infection!" We spent 5 days in the hospital with IV fluids & antibiotic cocktail. Now, not only does he STILL have these issues, but he also has a constant stream of phlegm down his throat, which Durante attributes to the surgery. Durante has no other advice, & he plays down his symptoms like hes a big baby. UNREAL.

Yes, I waited for an hour or so and now I know why...He spent 25 minutes with me, listening evaluating and going over each and every medication he was perscribing me. Every visit since has been just as thorough and clear. I am very glad that I have to wait for an hour for him because he gives me every bit of time and attention I need. So glad I didnt bail after the first visit. The need for a Rheumatologist means you will be in for the long haul, patience is key. Have faith he WILL listen and take every step to ensure you are on the right path.

Dr. Tina Robinson is one of THE BEST doctors with Kaiser. When she moved to a different location I also moved, as did most of her patients, to keep her as my doctor. She takes time to get to know her patients & we are on a first name basis. IF she ever left Kaiser I would drop Kaiser & follow her to another office. She has been my PCP for many years & I have NEVER been disappointed with the care I received from this kind, knowledgeable, physician. She takes time to really listen to my concerns & puts my fears, about anything, to rest. I highly recommend her as your PCP if you are in the S. Atlanta area & Kaiser is your insurance. I saw her today & was told I must have spine & neck surgery. She put my fears to rest & I plan on taking her advice now as well as in the future.

He also uses email to correspond with his patients (send lab results, ask how you're doing etc.) so he continues his communication with you even after your appointment. He also seems to be a much more modern doctor than others.

I have been going to Dr. Hodges for almost 4 years now. I originally went because of my coccyx which after several injections he recomended removing. Had my tail bone removed 2 1/2 years ago with no more problems in that area. I have since developed spondylelostesis, degenerative disc disease, a bone spur in my neck, osteoarthritis and Fibromyalgia. I continue to have regular visits with Dr. Hodges and his assistant whom I both have allot of confidence in my care. Dr. Hodges will not do back surgery if it will not do any good, I have a bulging disc as well and he wont do anything to my back until my other problems are under control. I respect a doctor very much for not shoving surgery down my throat when he doesn't think it is in my best interest at the time. I would definitely and do often recommend him to my family and friends.

Dr. Mollabashy correctly and efficiently diagnosed my grade II cartilage tumor in my shoulder.  He explained to me very clearly what my situation was without giving me unneeded worry or ambiguity. It was easy to schedule appointments.  After an initial biopsy, I recieved the results on Monday and was in surgery that Thursday.  Surgery went very well and I felt confident in Dr. Mollabashy.  My tumor was removed and rotator cuff reattached.  Follow up questions and appointments have been easy to take care of. I am very satisfied with this surgeon. I highly recommend him.

Ughhh...worst Kaiser EVER. Now, don't get me wrong, overall I love Kaiser insurance and they typically do a great job. However, this location is simply awful. I called while on my way to my appointment to refill a prescription and was asked to hold. I am used to this when calling Kaiser pharmacies, they always ask you to hold, but it's usually only a minute or two. This place though, I was literally on hold when I walked in the door 20 minutes later. When I got up to the counter to order my prescription I asked if I should continue to hold or hang up my call, I know smartass. Next up was checking in for my appointment, 10 minute line, then another 10 minute wait for the nurse who told me I as late for my appointment. I explained to her that I actually arrived 10 minutes early but you & your receptionist kept me waiting to equal "late". By the time I got into the doctors office I was more than annoyed, and after another 20 minute wait I was literally getting up to leave when the doctor walked it. He apologized for running late and asked if I was ready, I told him that after waiting for the last 40 minutes I was more than ready to get this over with. Although the doctor (for my annual exam for those of you who are wondering) was nice the entire experience was a disaster full of rude staff members with no sense of urgency and a complete lack of reality. I think I will be switching locations.

Dr. Tierney is an absolute gem of a doctor. We are forever grateful for the tender care and sweetness he has shown our daughter for the first year of her life. Never condescending and full of quiet humor, Dr. Tierney is always at the ready to patiently answer a new parent's questions that range from the absurd to more profound concerns. His sensibilities and kindness are refreshing as we try to navigate the terrain of parenting. Never dismissive and ever steady, we always look forward to seeing him and value his advice and huge heart. Once you see how he speaks to your dear babe or asks how you're doing, you will feel it. Some docs are aces on the mound.

I am new to the area and had my first appointment with Dr. Goldsborough when my daughter became ill with headaches and stomach pains for several days- I found her to be extremely thorough in her examination as well as had an understanding bedside manner. She explained all of her thoughts to us clearly as she explored different possible diagnoses and took us very seriously - She was additionally helpful in recommending other physicians with names and numbers which we needed, being new to the area. I was so pleased that we found a physician that was every bit as good as the one we left out of state.

Dr. Hidalgo is one of the best plastic surgeons in NYC. I have seen him for three different procedures all of which have the most natural results, which is exactly what I wanted. Dr. Hidalgo continues to be ranked as one of NYs best by other doctors. I spoke with one general practitioner who described Dr. Hidalgos work as meticulous. You can get a sense of that by merely coming in for a consolation. In his office there are drawings that Dr. Hidalgo has done of before and after procedures. These meticulous renderings, with their exacting detail, is a window into the artistry that Dr. Hidalgo brings to his surgical practice. He is not only an experienced doctor and a skilled surgeon, he also has an eye for proportion and detail that is essential to an outstanding plastic surgeon. Looking for a surgeon and making the decision to have cosmetic surgery can be daunting experience. For me, Dr. Hidalgo and his staff helped to make that experience a pleasant one.

Dr. Chu has been our family physician for approx. 13 years. He is a rare find in this new age of HMO's, PPO's, etc. He is extremely patient centered and takes the time to look at each patient in a holistic way; you feel as though you have someone that not only has a high level of expertise, but also someone that you feel comfortable sharing your concerns with- without being brushed off or minimized. Although I am sure that he has an extremely full plate, supervising interns, teaching, etc., he still remains accessible and makes his patients feel valued in a way that is reminiscent of the days when the doctor patient relationship was truly considered important and trusting.
